  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Bringing the \"cleaned\" money back into the economy as seemingly legitimate funds.\n\nMoney laundering is a criminal offense because it allows criminals to profit from and continue illegal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption. Governments and international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), work to combat money laundering through laws, regulations, and enforcement mechanisms.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. Financial institutions and other businesses are also required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs to detect and report suspicious activities.",
